1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
 So now I want to show you another example of many to many from an application that's near and dear to my heart and that's the autograder that I use for most of my online classes.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:18,000
 So one of the things the autograder has to know is like who is in what course so that we can track grades based on people and courses.

3
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:26,000
 And so this is the data model and it's a little bit different syntax. You sort of see one to many. It's using what's called crow's feet.

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:33,000
 And you see this little crow foot and that's like a many when it sort of spreads out and then you sort of have this one.

5
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:40,000
 And there's various little ways and one or more or zero or more. And so there's little, it's called a crow's foot diagram.

6
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:49,000
 But these diagrams ultimately are capturing the same thing whether these relationships are many to many or one to many and what the cardinality of each end of the relationship is.

7
00:00:49,000 --> 00:01:00,000
 And this is showing a person table, a course table, and a membership table. And this is a very common thing that we have to solve in educational systems.

8
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:09,000
 And it's a little bit more sophisticated than the previous one, which I thought was beautifully elegant and simple, but I want to show you this one as well.

9
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:19,000
 And so what we have here is basically a people are in courses, right? A person can be in many courses and a course can have many people.

10
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 So it's a many to many relationship. We create a through table. We'll call it a member table.

11
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:34,000
 We end up just like before with two one to many's pointing out or many to ones pointing outwards. So we have a person ID and a course ID in the member table.

12
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:43,000
 All three of these tables have primary keys of ID, ID and ID. And then we put the little tiny sort of virtual set in here.

13
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:52,000
 So that at a person you can just look at a virtual set of their courses and a course you can say who are the members of this course.

14
00:01:52,000 --> 00:02:02,000
 Now we're gonna do one more thing that's a little bit different here and that is often the simplest of through tables is literally an ID and two foreign keys.

15
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 And as a matter of fact, some people, Django doesn't like doing this, but some people don't even include the ID field.

16
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:17,000
 And they just make the combination of the two foreign keys as a unique ID inside. And if you're doing databases directly, you can actually do that.

17
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:26,000
 But here's a thing that you can also do. So if you think about in a teaching and learning situation, people aren't just members of courses.

18
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 They are members of courses and they have a role. And is that role as a learner, a teaching assistant, or an instructor, or perhaps they're the departmental administrator, right?

19
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:46,000
 And that is an attribute of the connection, right? The connection between a person and a course is the membership.

20
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 And oh, by the way, they're not just a member, they're a member with some metadata, okay?

21
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:59,000
 And so sometimes we add data to the through table and it's actually quite useful and it's really the only place to model this kind of data.

22
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:05,000
 Because somebody might be in a course as a teacher and they might be in a different course as a student.

23
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:11,000
 So you can't just say this person is always a teacher or they're always a student. You can't say that. It depends on the context.

24
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:21,000
 And so that's why at the connection between a particular person and a particular course, we actually model the role that they have in that course.

25
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:27,000
 So here we go. So we're going to have a person in a course.

26
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:36,000
 And we're going to have a through table, a membership. And so we're gonna send these things back and forth to each other.

27
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:44,000
 And this membership is the tricky one. And so we have a foreign key over to person and a foreign key over to course.

28
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:55,000
 And we're gonna model some information. We're gonna model a created date at, and this is a date time field. This is another feature that basically says let's make a created underscore at.

29
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:05,000
 And dear Django, I'm not even gonna set this value. Please, when I create this, a new record here, populate this at the current date and time.

30
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 And if I make a change to it, change the updated at.

31
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:19,000
 And it's a common pattern in lots of tables to put these two lines in. And it's so common that we often call them the same field.

32
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:24,000
 So you'll look in somebody's Django model and you'll see created at and you'll see updated at.

33
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 And so that's another thing we're modeling at the connection in the through table.

34
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 And so the other thing we're going to do is have the role. Now the example that you use in local library, they make this role I think a string.

